  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining App Requirements**\n\nOkay, I\'m working on clarifying the specifications for this web application. The focus is on a user workflow, not client-facing features. It needs to accept uploaded photos, and the client provided an example design, including hotlinking HTML images. I\'m focusing on the upload process as the central core of the solution, as this drives the entire thing.\n\n\n**Considering Data Storage Options**\n\nOkay, now I\'m evaluating the best data storage strategy for the uploaded photos. The goal is simple: I upload, modify if needed, and approve for production. This means I require download capabilities too. I\'m exploring options from local storage up to cloud persistence, specifically looking at Firebase integration. I need durable storage for this.\n\n\n**Evaluating Storage Approaches**\n\nI\'m now honing in on the ideal storage approach, specifically for this single-user workflow. It\'s becoming clear that a robust React application with either local persistence or server-side JSON storage might be sufficient. Thinking about local states, React Context, and client-side storage for simpler apps, I feel it will be appropriate.\nIf a server-side route is built, the uploads can be stored server-side.\nThis is not for multiple users, so no need for OAuth/API integration for mock data. A standard Express and persistent storage for development, modification, approval, and downloading is required.\n\n\n**Exploring Server & Client Sides**\n\nI\'m now determining how to proceed with a Vite app. I\'m checking for pre-existing packages (found Express and TypeScript) and reviewing the file tree, which lacks a dedicated server file. I\'m weighing options: IndexedDB/localStorage client-side or building a custom server. I\'m leaning toward a client-side approach using IndexedDB for image storage, given its robustness and large size capacity. Alternatively, I can provide a server-side route as an option.\n\n\n**Analyzing User Requests**\n\nI\'m now diving into the user request to nail down the desired functionality and aesthetic. I\'ve taken note of the \"Gallery Minimalist\" theme specifications, including the color palette and font choices. I need to make sure I import those fonts. I\'m focusing on the workflow, especially the \"Upload Photo,\" \"List/Grid of Items,\" and \"Details View\" components to build the design features.\n\n\n**Defining Image Workflow**\n\nOkay, I\'m now outlining the functionality for photo modification and management. I\'m focusing on features like editing image fields (title, client, notes, etc.), style selections (using chips with a framed state), and frame options. I\'ll include standard mat width and dimensions selection, alongside status management (\"Pending,\" \"Drafted,\" \"Approved\"). There must be an \"Approve for Production\" button and downloadable options.\n\n\n**Implementing Image Functionality**\n\nI\'m now implementing actual image downloading, cropping, and framing download features. I\'m focusing on the user workflow. The recent details clarified the purpose: I upload, make changes, approve, and download. It turns out the client needs to download the approved images as well. I\'m also now exploring utilizing the Gemini API to optionally offer an AI portrait enhancer/style visualizer to generate sketch descriptions, suggestions, or simulate styles, though it wasn\'t explicitly requested.\n\n\n**Assessing Infrastructure Requirements**\n\nI\'m now determining the optimal database approach for this \"my workflow\" application. I\'m focusing on local versus server-side storage. IndexedDB seems ideal for durable client-side storage, especially given its ability to handle large image files, and, as an alternative, I\'m considering using an Express backend for accessible, hosted image storage.\n\n\n**Designing App Architecture**\n\nI\'m now focusing on a robust, elegant IndexedDB solution for the front-end, with JSON export/import and download features, emphasizing durability and performance. It appears perfect; IndexedDB permits storing Blobs directly up to several gigabytes with 100% resolution. Then, I will design a magnificent \"Gallery Minimalist\" workspace.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 14
      nanos: 619670874
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
