    thinking: "**Considering Input Mechanisms**\n\nI\'m now exploring how best to handle the user\'s input. The URL format is clear, but I am wondering if I can extract the essential \"Form ID\" directly from the user to reduce unnecessary steps. It might be more convenient to accept either the full URL or simply the ID.\n\n\n**Clarifying Fetch Methods**\n\nI\'ve hit a slight snag, but it\'s shaping up. My current thought is centered around the Google Forms API\'s requirements. Can I fetch responses using the \"published\" URL\'s ID (`1FAIpQL...`), or do I need the editable form ID? I\'m developing strategies to accommodate both. Accepting either the editable Form ID or the viewform URL is a better design. If the latter doesn\'t work, I\'ll provide clear instructions to switch to the edit ID, which is excellent. I\'m focusing on user-friendliness now, which is a great approach.\n\n\n**Integrating Google Forms**\n\nI\'m now integrating Google Forms. It hit me\342\200\224what if I fetch responses and import them as new artwork entries? This could handle client intake or spec requests. Using Google login, I\'d fetch form data, display the form\'s title and description, list recent responses, and let the user \"Import as Portrait Sketch,\" which is fantastic! I am also considering how to display the form questions and latest responses within an integration panel for ease of use.\n\n\n**Refining Import Workflow**\n\nI\'m now refining the import workflow for Google Form responses into our portrait database. I\'m exploring an advanced mapping feature: users could map form questions directly to our database fields, which has smart auto-mapping and customization options for each import! This \"Import\" button would instantly insert the data into the local artwork list. I am considering that file uploads (like photos) from Google Forms API are not easy to support, but text fields are excellent. I\'m also considering embedding the form in an `<iframe>` within a dedicated \"Upload/New Portrait Modal.\"\n\n\n**Verifying Implementation Feasibility**\n\nI\'m now investigating how to build a full integration, and I\'ve come to a pretty good conclusion. Embedding the Google Form in an `<iframe>` is easy, and it gives the option to provide a standard intake form for submissions. I have proposed an \"Interactive Intake Form\" and an \"Import Bureau\" section, and it is a complete solution. I\'m verifying the OAuth setup now.\n\n\n**Confirming OAuth Setup**\n\nI\'m now dealing with the OAuth setup and realized that I must immediately call `set_up_oauth` with `userConfirmedInUI: true`. I am setting `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/forms` as the scope, because it is the requested scope. The `user_confirmed_in_ui` metadata confirmed the user already accepted the terms.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will call the OAuth setup tool with the confirmed `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/forms` scope. This is a critical requirement from the Workspace integration skill guidelines."
